<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Tell me a Tale, Uncle Bilbo<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.48)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11684'>Ross "Nuxxy" Done</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11684&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 25, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> You have a legend idea for a deck. Eagerly, you dismantle your playing deck and build it. But to your dismay, it ends up 40 cards a side. And you know that if you toss cards to bring it down to something reasonable, it won&#39;t work. And if you play it as 40 cards per side, you just don&#39;t get the cards you need. What do you do?<br>
<br>
The solution is a card-drawing mechanism. Some way to get more than 8 cards per turn. There are many available. Gandalf, Elrond, the &quot;Book of Mazarbul&quot;, a host of events from all cultures, and even the site 1 or 3 ally tricks. The problem? Adding them brings the card total even higher. And you need to get them out right at the beginning. It&#39;s a waste if you only draw them at site 8. What you need is a readily available and usable draw mechanism that fits into the theme of your deck. Take a good look and find one.<br>
<br>
The Realms of the Elf-lords expansion has brought some new possibilities is this area. And the one is tales. Before ROTEL, having many tales was generally something that belonged to Dwarven players. You need only look at Gloin&#39;s game text to realize why. But now nearly every culture has playable tales. The exception being Gandalf, but that&#39;s a small loss since it&#39;s already the best card drawing culture, and he has one thing no one else has: spells.<br>
<br>
So let&#39;s take a look at the proposed draw mechanism. First is &quot;Bilbo Baggins&quot;. Either version will do. And then the key is the &quot;Red Book of Westmarch&quot;. It says: &quot;Possession. Tale. Plays to your support area. Each time you play a tale, you may spot Bilbo to draw a card.&quot; <br>
<br>
The principle then being that every tale you play allows you to draw a card. And ROTEL effects this how? Let&#39;s take a look at how it could be used for each culture...<br>
<br>
Dwarven: A Dwarven tale deck has always been a possibility. Add the new Dwarven citadel card - &quot;Mines of Khazad-Dûm&quot;. Play a tale and you not only draw a card, but heal up to 4 wounds from Dwarven companions as well. Also, as nice as the &quot;Book of Mazarbul&quot; is, it only kicks in after site 4. This gives you a draw from the start. Also, Dwarves have a renowned weakness to conditions, and &quot;Bilbo Baggins, Well-spoken Gentlehobbit&quot; can help with that. Plus, &quot;Gimli&#39;s Pipe&quot; can help as well - as we&#39;ll see later.<br>
<br>
Elven: Which is the best Legolas? &quot;Greenleaf&quot;, obviously. But whereas he uses directed archery, the ROTEL &quot;Son of Thranduil&quot; uses a high archery total. Which is nice, because with &quot;A Ranger&#39;s Versatility&quot; errated, &quot;Greenleaf&quot; and &quot;Aragorn&#39;s Bow&quot; don&#39;t quite pack the same punch. So let&#39;s use the ROTEL mass archery. You&#39;ll want &quot;Son of Thranduil&quot;, &quot;The Tale of Gil-galad&quot; and &quot;The Splendor of Their Banners&quot;. 2 tales, and already a possible archery total of 5. Add other archer companions and the site 6 archery allies, and you have some scary archery totals. Besides lot&#39;s of &quot;The White Arrows of Lorien&quot;. The problem? &quot;Cave Troll&#39;s Chain&quot;, &quot;Spies of Saruman&quot; and the like. Skip the archery phase, and then what? Even with &quot;Dismay Our Enemies&quot; and the &quot;Long-knives of Legolas&quot;, Elves suck at skirmishing. That&#39;s why you have a card called &quot;Voice of Nimrodel&quot;. Exert an Elf at a river or forest (which with &quot;Son of Thranduil&quot; you should be aiming for), to cancel a skirmish. And guess what? It may be skirmish phase, but it&#39;s a tale. So spot Bilbo to draw a card. Yep - during the skirmish phase. Helps with the Elves other ROTEL strategy - moving twice. And might as well add in &quot;Songs of the Blessed Realm&quot; to remove a burden with each tale played. And maybe most versatile of all, you can play one or more &quot;The Council of Elrond&quot; to play the &quot;Red Book of Westmarch&quot; or any other tale from your draw deck.<br>
<br>
Gondor: Pre-ROTEL, Gondor&#39;s tales were limited to &quot;The Saga of Elendil&quot; and &quot;The Choice of Luthien&quot; (and &quot;The Last Alliance of Elves and Men&quot; which is an Elven card). But now there are a bunch of nice ones. &quot;Gondor Bowmen&quot; is so nice. Storable archery, and +2 each. And I traded mine. Aaaarrghh!<br>
&quot;Banner of the White Tree&quot;, &quot;Might of Numenor&quot; and &quot;Some Who Resisted&quot; are also not only tales, but all play during the maneuver phase, and so draw you a card without worrying about the rule of four. Finally, &quot;Answering the Cries&quot; allows you to discard your Gondor tales to pump Aragorn or Boromir, just in case. Worth it? For me, only if you want to use &quot;Might of Numenor&quot; and &quot;Some Who Resisted&quot; as pump cards, as it&#39;s only from hand and during the skirmish phase. But that may be a valid strategy anyway. All the other tales either pump by more, or are worth more when used properly. Though if you have Gondor Bowmen in hand and your last Gondor companion is otherwise going to die, then obviously.<br>
<br>
Shire: For using Bilbo and the Red Book as a draw mechanism, not very amazing. But still useful. There are a couple of tales played during the fellowship phase which will draw you cards. It&#39;s always something to consider, especially since you will likely be using Biblo&#39;s native ability. Special mention does go to one card. Finally, you can use &quot;Stone Troll&#39;s&quot;. Just look at Fror to see how much a +3 boost versus Uruk-hai can help. And any boost against Trolls (of which we will eventually see more!) is good. If you are going to play Bilbo for those, might as well draw a card while you&#39;re about it.<br>
<br>
So there are valid reasons to have Bilbo and the Red Book in your deck. But how do you get them out quickly? Well, if you&#39;re willing to forgo &quot;The Prancing Pony&quot; or anything as your site 1, you can have Bilbo out by site 1 with &quot;Hobbiton Party Field&quot;. The Red Book is a little more tricky. Basically only &quot;The Council of Elrond&quot; helps with that.<br>
<br>
But there&#39;s more value to this little combo than just card drawing. First, you have to choose your Bilbo. &quot;Retired Adventurer&quot; allows you to recycle Shire cards. Which is nice if you loose your Red Book, or play any pipeweed. &quot;Well-spoken Gentlehobbit&quot; may help with getting rid of pesky support area Shadow conditions. Though unless you can recycle, you don&#39;t really want to toss your hard-earned tales.<br>
It may well come down to which site suits you. &quot;Retired Adventurer&quot; is site 3, and so can be healed by Elrond, while &quot;Well-spoken Gentlehobbit&quot; is site 1 and can be healed by &quot;Hobbit Party Guest&quot;. Both of course can be healed by &quot;Frodo, Old Bilbo&#39;s Heir&quot;, which is probably better. Because allies have been taking a bit of a knock lately, what with &quot;Uruk Raiders&quot; and other cards making their appearance. Most decks have some sort of ally kill. Which brings us to the rest of the equipment no Bilbo should be without.<br>
<br>
First up, &quot;Consorting With Wizards&quot;. Such a sweet card. In your face, &quot;Tower Assassins&quot; and Nazgul ally killers! No more wounds for Bilbo. And combined cards like &quot;Boromir&#39;s Horn&quot;, provided he&#39;s not overwhelmed, you have a nearly invulnerable Hobbit ally! Plus he can exert to remove twilight.<br>
Next, &quot;Bilbo&#39;s Pipe&quot;. Recycle all your tales, just when your opponent gets to discard them. Plus an extra pipe.<br>
Lastly, you can even equip him with a &quot;Frying Pan&quot; or &quot;Hobbit Sword&quot;. He may help wonders to beat down some Orcs, especially those pesky Isengard ones. With &quot;Consorting With Wizards&quot;, you can exhaust him with the &quot;Frying Pan&quot;, lose, and still survive.<br>
<br>
Bilbo out early is also lovely for Hobbit decks. &quot;Practically Everyone Was Invited&quot; will help by drawing any Hobbit you choose - companion or ally.<br>
<br>
The final nifty trick any Bilbo deck can use is to note that Bilbo can count as that second Hobbit (obviously along with Frodo) for triggering &quot;Deft In Their Movements&quot; (wonderful for choke decks) and &quot;Not Feared in Sunlight&quot; (die nasty Nazgul).<br>
<br>
So what possible deck ideas does this produce? I&#39;m not going to list actual card numbers, and will only mention tale wielding decks. Which are...<br>
<br>
Dwarven: Mentioned already. You use the 4 Dwarves - Gimli, Gloin, Fror and Farin, and lots of Dwarven tales. Dwarves really need a cycling method. A couple of &quot;Stone Trolls&quot; will boost them nicely against Uruk-hai, making your only real worry Nazgul. Which is why you add &quot;Not Feared in Sunlight&quot;. You may not even need skirmish pump cards.<br>
The suggested Bilbo would be &quot;Well-spoken Gentlehobbit&quot;, to help remove Shadow conditions. &quot;Frodo, Old Bilbo&#39;s Heir&quot; will take care of healing him. And for recycling you can either use &quot;Storm of Argument&quot;, or give Bilbo his pipe, Gimli his, and Frodo can grab his (if you use &quot;Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain Race&quot;) or the Gaffer&#39;s. &quot;Mines of Khazad-Dûm&quot; will hopefully take card of Dwarven healing...have yet to test it. You then have a rather mean Dwarf deck. If you feel the need, you can add Gandalf with &quot;Gandalf&#39;s Staff&quot;, &quot;Glamdring&quot;, &quot;Narya&quot; and possibly &quot;Gandalf&#39;s Pipe&quot; as an extra companion, or some speed-bump &quot;Dwarf Guards&quot;. They do wonders with a &quot;Disquiet of Our People&quot;.<br>
Final note - to pump Gloin, don&#39;t always use &quot;Stairs of Khazad-dûm&quot;. First decide on tales you really want, like &quot;Beneath the Mountains&quot;, &quot;Book of Mazarbul&quot; and &quot;Greatest Kingdom of My People&quot;. And then, if there is no real Moria threat in your area, rather use &quot;Till Durin Wakes Again&quot;. Just as cheap, potentially more useful. It heals every Dwarven companion, and can be stacked. Yes, only one or two sites, but that may be your life or death. It&#39;s not nicknamed the &#39;Bridge of Death&#39; for nothing.<br>
<br>
Elven/Gondor: So many possibilities here, but personally I&#39;d like to try a pipeweed mega-archery/skirmish/ranger deck. Which is? High archery totals, ranger twilight denial, and 3 or 4 strong companions to kill whatever survives. All based around &quot;Legolas, Son of Thranduil&quot; kitted out with &quot;Splendor of Their Banners&quot;, &quot;Tale of Gil-galad&quot;, &quot;Bow of the Galadhrim&quot; and &quot;Long-knives&quot;. He can skirmish and adds much to archery. &quot;Arwen, Daughter of Elrond&quot; with &quot;Gwemigil&quot; and an &quot;Elven Bow&quot; will help, especially against Nazgul. &quot;Aragorn, King in Exile&quot; with an &quot;Armor&quot;, &quot;Last Alliance&quot;, &quot;Aragorn&#39;s Bow&quot; and either two &quot;Flaming Brands&quot; or one and a &quot;Ranger Sword&quot;. Lastly, a fully kitted &quot;Boromir, Lord of Gondor&quot;, with an &quot;Armor&quot;, &quot;Last Alliance&quot;, &quot;Flaming Brand&quot;, &quot;Blade of Gondor&quot;, &quot;Boromir&#39;s Shield&quot;, &quot;Boromir&#39;s Cloak&quot; and the &quot;Horn of Boromir&quot;. The three rangers all get &quot;No Stranger to the Shadow&quot;, and then lots of &quot;Gondor Bowmen&quot;, recycled via &quot;Bilbo&#39;s Pipe&quot;. Aragorn gets his pipe, and Frodo gets the Gaffer&#39;s. Add &quot;Elrond, Herald to Gil-galad&quot; and &quot;Vilya&quot;, with a few &quot;Secret Sentinels&quot;. Use &quot;Bilbo Baggins, Retired Adventurer&quot; so he can get healed by Elrond and can recycle the pipeweed. &quot;Pathfinders&quot; to make sure you get your sites. Lastly, &quot;Stone Trolls&quot; for everybody.<br>
If that&#39;s too many cards, you can drop either Aragorn, Arwen or Boromir. The focus is on Legolas and recycling &quot;Gondor Bowmen&quot;. The idea is that at most only a couple of minions (if any) will survive, to be killed by the few companions. Few companions, mostly rangers, means little twilight in the first place. You could even add a couple of &quot;Deft in Their Movements&quot; and two &quot;Bill the Pony&quot; to provide even less twilight. And don&#39;t forget the &quot;Council of Elrond&quot; and &quot;Songs of the Blessed Realm&quot;. Maybe even &quot;The Shards of Narsil&quot;, if you&#39;re worried about your &quot;Gondor Bowmen&quot; being discarded. As I said, so many possibilities.<br>
<br>
So where&#39;s the catch? Making a 40-card Free Peoples side is possible, and playable, with Bilbo and the Red Book. Every tale virtually becomes a free card space. But the trick is balance. You have to have 40 shadow cards too. Which means you either build a Shadow side with it&#39;s own drawing mechanism, or one that plays a lot of &#39;redundant&#39; cards - meaning ones that are cheap and can be tossed if necessary when reconciling. But who wants to play Moria anyway? :)<br>
<br>
All I can suggest is that you give it a go. If you can build in Shadow drawing mechanism as well, you may be able to add those extra cards that you always wanted to play, those that were nifty, but not necessary. Now you can.<br>
<br>
